sec.p:
CLC is an unmixed combustion technology where fuel and combustion air have no direct contact [5, 6]. Pure oxygen for fuel combustion is provided by a metal oxide (MeOx) called the oxygen carrier (OC) in form of lattice oxygen. The OC enters two different reaction zones located in two reactors, according to Fig. 1. In the air reactor (AR), the OC takes up oxygen during a reaction with air (Reaction 1). The combustion of the fuel occurs in the fuel reactor (FR), where the transfer of oxygen to the fuel (CnHm) is enabled, as seen in Reaction 2. [38] Thereby the OC is reduced and oxidation is again necessary for completing the loop of the two reactions. Due to the absence of nitrogen, the exhaust gas of the FR consists of CO2 and H2O. The circulation of OC between the reactors transfers the oxygen necessary for combustion and the heat required to maintain the heat balance in the system [39].
